        <article class="comment-article com-show" id="tree_43488953" data-cid="43488953">
    <div id="comment_43488953">
        <header data-points="1" data-reason="Normal">
            <h3 class="comment-title" data-subject="Re:Wrong."><i class="com-toggle fa fa-caret-down"></i>Re:Wrong.<span> (1)</span></h3>
            <h4 class="avatar-tiny"><a href="//beta.slashdot.org/~demonlapin" class="author" title="author name and user ID">demonlapin (527802) </a> | about a year ago | <a href="//beta.slashdot.org/comments.pl?sid=3663727&cid=43488953">(#43488953)</a></h4>
        </header>
        <div id="comment_body_43488953" class="comment-wrapper" data-points="1" data-reason="Normal">
            <div class="comment-body">Not Amazon's fault. Apple's. Amazon used to sell ebooks at ebook prices - new $18 hardbacks for $9.99 in Kindle Edition - until the "agency model" gave the publishers the upper hand. <br> <br>I don't think Amazon is a perfect company, but they definitely are pro-consumer in the same way that great multi-supplier salesmen all are - they want the best deal for the customer, not the supplier, and they collect their money for providing good customers to the suppliers.</div>
